positions.title: Product Design & Development | Building Digital Prototypes | Technical Package Creation | Production Quality Control

bio:
As an Industrial Designer, I leverage 7+ years of product development experience to create and deliver innovative design solutions that meet evolving user needs. My approach is threefold: I translate and illustrate technology concepts, lead the 3D CAD modeling/rendering process, and establish manufacturing paradigms. 

Throughout my career, I have utilized this approach to build winning products from the ground up. At Pretty Knotty, for instance, I built and launched 2 new hair tie products for athletes that drove immediate revenue for the company. I did this by designing product using sketches and 3D models, developing quality controls, and optimizing the manufacturing process. 

The other main reason for my success is delivering on-schedule and on-budget projects with minimum changes in scope. This is how I was able to address resource constraints for 8 custom and semi-custom product design projects while working with geographically dispersed teams across US and China at Nomadic Display. 

I have also contributed to the industry via research and writing on product development, manufacturing, and restoring. My articles are published on LinkedIn, Solidsmack, and Makers Row.

If you want to work with someone who develops concepts into cutting-edge industrial products, exhibits superior project management skills, and builds research materials and processes, I can be reached via email at jacob.eberhart@gmail.com.

Key Projects: ALICE Backpack Reconfiguration & Design, Custom Panels for Cornhole Boards, iPhone Attachment Design & Wipe Dispenser Design.

Specialties: CNC Milling, 3D Printing, Materials Sourcing and Testing, CRM, Hand Sketching/Rendering, Searching, Drafting Design and Utility Patents.

summary: A natural communicator, I have dedicated my career to enabling people to be included, engaged, present and able to express themselves. Wolfpack Engagement is an experiment toward fulfilling those outcomes, and it’s a counter-intuitive one. We think that when people are in the same room, face to face, that smartphones are an unprecedented distraction. They are so counter-productive. The apps on them have been meticulously constructed to be so, tapping into the deepest recesses of our brain to keep us coming back, hundreds of times a day. Of course smartphones are an amazing tool. We need them. Yet when we are face-to-face, we must find a way to pull ourselves away from the world inside the smartphone, and into the real world, full of real people, right in front of our eyes. But we still need a way to communicate in tandem, tapping into the collective wisdom and including every single person in the room. That’s why we hand out clickers. They are so cheap, effective, and game-changing. But only if done right. That’s what I do. I create the content and train people how to use Audience/Classroom Response Systems. Because the tech itself is not a silver bullet. We must create interesting & meaningful questions with which to use the clickers to answer. Not just test questions. We need to use them to elicit the collaboration of the people in the room, all the people, and creating such questions is more of an art than a science. I help companies, trainers, teachers, speakers, market researchers, and event designers to create the questions they need answered, capture the data in real-time, react to it in real-time, and try to make sense of what it means. We all know that QR codes and other polling apps result in disappointingly low participation rates. And why are brands spending money putting their logos on throwaway lanyards & bags at events? Redirect that spend, embrace the humans in front of you, and let me show you and your team the power of these amazing devices. Cheers
